Drought analysis for gcam talk

library(survival)        # standard R package for survival analysis
library(stayinalive)     # functions we developed for processing time series.
library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)
beta <- 0.25
year <- 2001:2100

Generate 100 years of data for 10 basins. Temperature increases over the course of the century according to Hectors RCP8.5 pathway. Droughts are between 1 and 2 years long in this simulation. The \(\beta\) value of 0.25 means that each degree of global temperature change should produce about a 28% increase in drought risk relative to the baseline.

hcore <- hector::newcore(system.file('input', 'hector_rcp85.ini', package='hector'))
invisible(hector::run(hcore,max(year)))
temps <- hector::fetchvars(hcore, year, hector::GLOBAL_TEMP())
Tgyr <- temps$value
Tgmon <- rep(Tgyr, rep(12, length(Tgyr)))   # convert to monthly values
ggplot(mapping=aes(x=year, y=Tgyr)) + geom_line(color='lightgrey', size=1.25) + 
    theme_solarized_2(light=FALSE)

nyear <- length(Tgyr)
nmonth <- 12*nyear
nbasin <- 20
set.seed(867-5309)
basindata <- gents(nbasin, nmonth, Tgmon, beta=beta)

Plot the pattern of drought in the basin data.

bd <- t(basindata)
colnames(bd) <- seq(1,nbasin)
bddf <- as.data.frame(bd)
bddf$month <- seq(1,nrow(bddf))
bddf2 <- tidyr::gather(bddf, key='basin', value='value', -month, convert=TRUE)
bddf2$drought <- bddf2$basin * bddf2$value
ggplot(data=bddf2, aes(x=month, y=drought)) + geom_point(color='lightgrey') + ylim(c(1,nbasin+1)) + ylab('Basin') +
    theme_solarized_2(light=FALSE)

The code below converts the basin time series to the event data frame required by the coxph function. Then we feed that to a simple Cox model.

events <- tsmat2event(basindata, Tgyr, 1)
events$basinid <- as.factor(events$basinid)
cph <- coxph(Surv(tstart, tstop, drought)~Tg, data=events)
summary(cph)

Marginal. The fit is just a tiny bit above one SE away from the right answer. However, the statistics are not good. The confidence intervals include no effect.

betafit <- cph$coefficients['Tg']
bh <- basehaz(cph)
h0 <- bh$hazard
calcsurv <- function(tg) {
    psi <- exp(tg*betafit)
    s <- exp(-psi*h0)
    data.frame(temperature=tg, time=bh$time, S=s)
}
pltdata <- dplyr::bind_rows(lapply(c(0,1,2,5), calcsurv))
pltdata$temperature <- paste(pltdata$temperature, 'deg C')
ggplot(data=pltdata, aes(x=time, y=S, color=temperature)) + geom_line(size=1.1) + 
    theme_minimal() + scale_color_manual(values=c('black','blue','green','red'))
